Aim: Write a PL/SQL function to find the reverse of a number.

Solution:
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION reverse_it(x IN INT) RETURN INT AS
  z INT;
  rev INT := 0;
  r INT;
BEGIN
  WHILE x > 0 LOOP
    r := MOD(x, 10);
    rev := (rev * 10) + r;
    x := TRUNC(x / 10);
  END LOOP;
  
  z := rev;
  RETURN z;
END;
/

Calling in PL/SQL Block:
BEGIN
  DECLARE a INT := 123456789;
  DECLARE c INT;
  
  c := reverse_it(a);
  DBMS_OUTPUT.put_line('The reverse of number is ' || c);
END;
/
Directly in SQL (if the function is deterministic and doesn't rely on PL/SQL features):
SELECT reverse_it(123456789) FROM dual;
*Note - DUAL is a special dummy table that exists in all Oracle databases. It is used primarily when you need to run a query that does not explicitly require a table reference, such as selecting a value, performing a calculation, or calling a function.

Explanation:
•	The reverse_it function accepts an integer (x) and returns its reverse.
•	It uses a WHILE loop to extract each digit of the number, reverses it, and stores the result in rev.
•	The reversed number is returned as the output.
Outcome: This practical helps students understand how to manipulate numbers in PL/SQL using loops and return values from functions.




# Functions in PL/SQL
1 .Calculate Total, Percentage & Division
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION Function_1(
marks1 NUMBER,
marks2 NUMBER,
marks3 NUMBER
)
RETURN NUMBER
IS
Total NUMBER;
Perc  NUMBER;
BEGIN
Total := marks1 + marks2 + marks3;
DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('Total : ' || Total);
Perc := Total / 3;
DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('Percentage : ' || Perc);
IF Perc > 75 THEN
DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('Distinction Division');
ELSIF Perc > 60 THEN
DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('First Class Division');
ELSE
DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('Fail');
END IF;
RETURN Perc;
END Function_1;
/
# Execution block
SET SERVEROUTPUT ON;
SELECT Function_1(35,55,85) FROM dual;
# OUTPUT:
FUNCTION_1(35,55,85)
58.3333333
Total : 175
Percentage : 58.33
Fail


